<p>
	And gazing at these graceful buildings are two American tourists worried that they look like complete morons as they wander in their funny gringo clothes with just five words of badly pronounced Spanish between them. 
</p>
<p>
	But this is a lot of the fun of travel. Do you, at home, spend the day trying to order a restaurant meal in pantomime? Do you, at home, wear a cocktail-length mini-dress to church? And do you, at home, try to give directions to a taxicab driver using only nouns in the singular? These engaging parlor games are yours to enjoy all day when you travel to a place far enough removed from the familiar. 
</p>
<h3>
	Some words about clothing
</h3>
<p>
	Americans, especially those of us from west of the 100th meridian, are notoriously poor dressers. In our region, neckties and nylons are ritual attire worn at funerals and weddings, and jeans and flip-flops are acceptable in most settings. When we go to Buenos Aires, we're always cautioned to dress better, in more sober colors, in nice shoes. 
</p>
<p>
	I found the costumes of Buenos Aires to be less formal than I expected. I guess I was anticipating seeing a lot of men in finely tailored suits, and women in monochrome couture ensembles, as I saw in Madrid. In Buenos Aires I saw many men in jeans, though these were neatly pressed jeans, and only the young wore the distressed scruffy styles. I saw fewer women in skirts and dresses than I see in the U.S. The fit for both men and women was very slim; hip-hop fashion doesn't seem to have much influence in Buenos Aires. I never saw, though most days the weather was warm, anybody dragging around in flip-flops. 
</p>
