<h3>
	Scams
</h3>
<p>
	One disappointing quality of the scams worked on tourists in Buenos Aires is that none of the methods are unique to the city. Read enough travel guides, and the rip-offs begin to sound the same. 
</p>
<p>
	Michael and I didn't encounter the mustard-squirting duos of pick-pocketers, though we met some Americans who did, in Plaza San Mart&iacute;n. We weren't robbed by armed youths, and my purse wasn't grabbed. But I think we did get scammed, though we disagree about what happened. 
</p>
<p>
	On Ayacucho 1365 is an enticing health food store called Natural Buenos Aires. The displays of whole-grain crackers and dried fruit brought us in from the street to buy some snacks. There was something furtive in the cashier's manner when he rang up our purchase: he mumbled the total amount we owed, and then cleared the display on the register. We didn't understand what he said (even after he mumbled it three times), nor could we check the total on the register. 
</p>
<p>
	Michael and I agree up to this point, but we don't when we try to remember the denomination of the bill Michael put down to pay. Using either of our memories, we still think we didn't get back the full amount of change, though, of course, we never learned really how much the charge was. The episode left us with a very unpleasant taste that none of the delicious snacks could remove. Moral of this story: if you shop at Natural Buenos Aires, and your Spanish isn't up to staging a confrontation, I suggest you watch your transaction 
	<strong>
		very carefully</strong>. 
</p>
